{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640866"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:19:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:19:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17842"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17842"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.21,0.09,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10556"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116705"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10556"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98693"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1992"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24617"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116705"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOne manner in which glucose is taken up by tissues is via insulin-stimulated glucose uptake. This involves changing the permeability of a cell membrane to glucose.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following tissues primarily uses insulin-stimulated glucose uptake?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Skeletal muscle, adipose tissue and heart","Liver, brain and kidney","Pancreas, spleen and lung","Intestine, skin and bone","Thyroid, adrenal gland and pituitary"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EInsulin-stimulated glucose uptake primarily occurs in \u003Cstrong\u003Eskeletal muscle, adipose tissue and heart\u003C/strong\u003E. These tissues express insulin-sensitive glucose transporters, which increase in number on the cell membrane in response to insulin, enhancing glucose uptake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver, brain and kidney\u003C/strong\u003E have different mechanisms for glucose uptake that are not primarily insulin-dependent. Similarly, the \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreas, spleen and lung\u003C/strong\u003E are not major sites of insulin-stimulated glucose uptake. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eintestine, skin and bone\u003C/strong\u003E do not primarily rely on insulin for glucose uptake. Finally, endocrine organs such as the \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid, adrenal gland and pituitary\u003C/strong\u003E do not primarily use insulin-stimulated glucose uptake.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Insulin-stimulated glucose uptake occurs in tissues that express insulin-sensitive glucose transporters.","Skeletal muscle, adipose tissue and heart are the primary tissues where insulin increases glucose uptake.","Insulin increases the number of glucose transporters on the cell membrane, enhancing glucose permeability."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 79; pg. 975."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type"